<ol start="2" class="has-large-font-size"><li>Starting a schedule </li></ol>



<p style="font-style:italic;font-weight:500;">Now you may have a study space, but is it useful like it should be? To assure the answer to this question is “yes,” you will need to start a schedule and stick to it. Without a schedule, the study space may barely end up being used as well as it could. For example, if you have work and school, those things could collide and lead to multitasking, which isn’t nearly as efficient as working on each thing at their own time. If you work from 9 am to 5 pm, make work your only objective during that time frame. People may think it would be more productive to work on a school project during work hours, but it is not because each task is not being done at its full potential. Your schoolwork will be waiting for you when you’re done so make the most out of your work time. Even if you don’t have work and only have homework, you may think doing chores in between would be effective, but it’s the same with trying to do school and work at the same time. </p>



<ol start="3" class="has-large-font-size"><li>Doing away with distractions </li></ol>



<p style="font-style:italic;font-weight:500;">The easiest way to stop your study space from being a study space is to be surrounded by distractions. Distractions are the biggest problem for someone who wants to complete their task. All distractions do is waste valuable time. Checking social media posts or having a tv show run in the background constantly, is going to make it near impossible to focus. Your brain is not going to go on auto pilot and do the work for you, so you need to respect your study time and push away these distractions. This may be hard when starting out, but if you do this enough times, you’ll see how much more productive you are. </p>



