<p>Just returned to FL from NY.</p>
<p><div data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_25097" style="width: 1450px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://nicalabela.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/20220505_113548.jpg"><img loading="lazy" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-25097" data-attachment-id="25097" data-permalink="http://leavingamerika.com/2022/06/06/for-no-one/20220505_113548/" data-orig-file="https://nicalabela.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/20220505_113548.jpg" data-orig-size="4032,3024" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{

}" data-image-title="hideaway" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://angryseraph.files.wordpress.com/2020/07/hideaway.jpg?w=198" data-large-file="https://angryseraph.files.wordpress.com/2020/07/hideaway.jpg?w=329" src="https://angryseraph.files.wordpress.com/2020/07/hideaway.jpg?w=329" alt="" class="wp-image-9065" width="191" height="290" srcset="https://angryseraph.files.wordpress.com/2020/07/hideaway.jpg?w=191 191w, https://angryseraph.files.wordpress.com/2020/07/hideaway.jpg?w=99 99w, https://angryseraph.files.wordpress.com/2020/07/hideaway.jpg?w=198 198w, https://angryseraph.files.wordpress.com/2020/07/hideaway.jpg 329w" sizes="(max-width: 191px) 100vw, 191px" /></figure>



<p>Hideaway<br><a href="https://angryangelbooks.com/2020/07/20/hideaway/">Angry Angel Books Review</a><br><a href="https://smile.amazon.com/Hideaway-Novel-Nora-Roberts-ebook/dp/B07WQHHQGM/ref=sr_1_14?qid=1652618661&s=digital-text&sr=1-14">Amazon Link</a></p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large is-resized"><img loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="7325" data-permalink="http://angryangelbooks.com/2018/02/20/the-great-alone/the-great-alone-2/" data-orig-file="https://angryseraph.files.wordpress.com/2018/02/the-great-alone.jpg" data-orig-size="330,499" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{

}" data-image-title="Seib" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/seib.jpg?w=194" data-large-file="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/seib.jpg?w=259" class="alignright wp-image-11404 size-medium" style="border:1px solid #000000;" src="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/seib.jpg?w=194" alt="" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/seib.jpg?w=194 194w, https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/seib.jpg?w=97 97w, https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/seib.jpg 259w" sizes="(max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></a>I have gone missing but I have not stopped reading.</p>
<p>That, I suppose, is a statement always at risk of being true. If so, then it’s more true than ever lately as I find my free time diminished and my workday lengthened by an untimely staff death. Once again, the universe has unveiled a nasty streak of larceny aimed at my time.</p>
<p>That theft has not yet driven me to oxymoronic forms (i.e., audiobooks) but it has driven me to more than one “book” stored on my phone. As my dear departed colleague, herself an avid reader, liked to say,  “You spend so much time waiting you ought to at least have a book with you.” That notion, and a bargain-basement price, explain the present volume.</p>
<p>More than once I’ve referenced the role <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Wall_Street_Journal" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em><strong>The Wall Street Journal</strong></em></a> played in my development as a young professional. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gerald-f-seib" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Gerald Seib</strong></a>, the author of this book, is presently the Executive Washington Editor for the paper and for a long time penned a weekly column on doings in the capital city. He’s precisely the sort of person you meet riding the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acela"><strong>Acela</strong></a> corridor, where I literally once bumped into him.</p>
<p><div data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_11415" style="width: 160px" class="wp-caption alignright"><img loading="lazy" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-11415" data-attachment-id="11415" data-permalink="https://anhonestcon.wordpress.com/2022/05/15/forces-of-chaos-and-anarchy/g_seib_wsj_dots/" data-orig-file="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/g_seib_wsj_dots.png" data-orig-size="450,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{

}" data-image-title="G_Seib_WSJ_dots" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="<p>Gerald Seib in the iconic WSJ dot llustration style.</p>
" data-medium-file="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/g_seib_wsj_dots.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/g_seib_wsj_dots.png?w=450" class="wp-image-11415 size-thumbnail" src="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/g_seib_wsj_dots.png?w=150" alt="" width="150" height="150" srcset="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/g_seib_wsj_dots.png?w=150 150w, https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/g_seib_wsj_dots.png?w=300 300w" sizes="(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px" /><p id="caption-attachment-11415" class="wp-caption-text">Gerald Seib in the iconic WSJ dot illustration style.</p></div></p>
<p>Here Seib provides <em>his </em>version of our recent politics. Political journalists are always tossing off lengthier versions of the first draft of history and the longer form doesn’t necessarily improve things. How can I say this kindly? Journalists are concerned with a coherent storyline. The tale’s the thing. They often ask important questions. But the analysis is typically less satisfying than I like.</p>
<p>You could rightfully argue that they’re doing their job and if they find an expert willing to lend <em>their</em> interpretation then there’s no issue. I’m willing to accept that. It just strikes me as thin gruel. Maybe it’s why newspapers seem less vital to me now.</p>
<p>In any case, Seib essentially uses his own career as a frame for the transformation of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Republican_Party_(United_States)" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Republican</strong></a> politics over the last 4 decades. That’s basically from the “<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Presidency_of_Ronald_Reagan" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Reagan revolution</strong></a>” to the age of “<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Make_America_Great_Again" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Make America Great Again</strong></a>.” I don’t want to pick fights, but anyone who sees these poles as two sides of the same coin, or as a story of mutation-free evolution, isn’t thinking clearly. They do, though, begin with a common impulse: throw the rascals out.</p>
<p><div data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_11417" style="width: 310px" class="wp-caption alignright"><img loading="lazy" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-11417" data-attachment-id="11417" data-permalink="https://anhonestcon.wordpress.com/2022/05/15/forces-of-chaos-and-anarchy/cwa/" data-orig-file="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/cwa.jpg" data-orig-size="1200,600" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{

}" data-image-title="CWA" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="<p>You could start a discussion of opposition and rage at the Contract With America.</p>
" data-medium-file="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/cwa.jpg?w=300" data-large-file="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/cwa.jpg?w=1024" class="size-medium wp-image-11417" src="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/cwa.jpg?w=300" alt="" width="300" height="150" srcset="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/cwa.jpg?w=300 300w, https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/cwa.jpg?w=600 600w, https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/cwa.jpg?w=150 150w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /><p id="caption-attachment-11417" class="wp-caption-text">You could start a discussion of opposition and rage at the Contract With America.</p></div></p>
<p>The story Seib tells is, by now,  familiar. Mid-century <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dwight_D._Eisenhower" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Eisenhower</strong></a>/<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Country_club_Republican" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Country Club Republicans</strong> </a>find themselves suddenly eclipsed by a group that so spectacularly lost the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1964_United_States_presidential_election" target="_blank" rel="noopener">1964 Presidential election</a> that any sort of resurrection seemed beyond fanciful.  If you’d told anyone in 1964 that Republicans would be in control in less than 20 years you’d have been thought bonkers. Yet you might question that achievement when you consider what came next.</p>
<p>First, there was the rise of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newt_Gingrich" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Newt Gingrich</strong></a>.  A would-be professor turned politician representing suburban <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atlanta" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Atlanta</strong></a>, Gingrich engineered a stunning Republican takeover of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_House_of_Representatives" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>House</strong></a>. That was just a prelude to turning himself into a legislative <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Icarus" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Icarus</strong></a>. But before immolating his political career Gingrich spurred real changes in legislation and in how the House operated.</p>
<p><div data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_11419" style="width: 310px" class="wp-caption alignright"><img loading="lazy" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-11419" data-attachment-id="11419" data-permalink="https://anhonestcon.wordpress.com/2022/05/15/forces-of-chaos-and-anarchy/gfc/" data-orig-file="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/gfc.jpg" data-orig-size="474,402" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{

}" data-image-title="GFC" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="<p>Adding fuel to the fire. Homes lost. Dreams shattered. And bailouts for Wall Street.</p>
" data-medium-file="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/gfc.jpg?w=300" data-large-file="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/gfc.jpg?w=474" class="wp-image-11419 size-medium" style="border:1px solid #000000;" src="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/gfc.jpg?w=300" alt="" width="300" height="254" srcset="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/gfc.jpg?w=300 300w, https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/gfc.jpg?w=150 150w, https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/gfc.jpg 474w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /><p id="caption-attachment-11419" class="wp-caption-text">Adding fuel to the fire. Homes lost. Dreams shattered. And bailouts for Wall Street.</p></div></p>
<p>Absent charismatic leadership those changes didn’t really stick in any meaningful way. One thing that fascinates me is cultural persistence. I’ve worked in at least two organizations that, in the name of self-preservation, decreed wholesale revolutions and overturned the majority of the staff. And yet years later self-defeating behaviors and policies remained in place. Why should the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Congress" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>United States Congress</strong></a> be any different?</p>
<p>Yet the underlying anger kept simmering and exploded again in the aftermath of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Financial_crisis_of_2007%E2%80%932008" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Global Financial Crisis</strong></a>. There are many ways to understand that mess. I’m particularly fond of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Harvey" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>David Harvey</strong></a>‘s <a href="https://youtu.be/qOP2V_np2c0" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Marxist </a>interpretation which manages to cram in every trope I learned from the red diaper baby brigade I studied with into 11 entertaining minutes. No matter the explanation, what’s indisputable was the outcome. The malefactors–the financial elites–got bailed out, collectively, by the little people.</p>
<p>As a business acquaintance from the southeast always says, “Tain’t right.” And so the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tea_Party_movement"><strong>Tea Party</strong> </a>movement emerged. In Seib’s telling the electoral success of the TPM in the 2010 midterms should have awakened everyone. Here was a group that could be,  and has been,  defined in many ways. Yet I haven’t seen a lot of use of the word i believe best describes their outlook: nihilism.</p>
<p><div data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_11412" style="width: 310px" class="wp-caption alignright"><a href="https://youtu.be/29E6GbYdB1c"><img loading="lazy" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-11412" data-attachment-id="11412" data-permalink="https://anhonestcon.wordpress.com/2022/05/15/forces-of-chaos-and-anarchy/horsefeathers-groucho/" data-orig-file="https://anhonestcon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/horsefeathers-groucho.jpg" data-orig-size="628,475" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{

}" data-image-title="ink-gif-website" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://ellenmint.files.wordpress.com/2020/08/ink-gif-website.gif?w=300" data-large-file="https://ellenmint.files.wordpress.com/2020/08/ink-gif-website.gif?w=800" src="https://ellenmint.files.wordpress.com/2020/08/ink-gif-website.gif?w=800" alt="" class="wp-image-3943" /></figure>



<p></p>



<div class="wp-block-image"><figure class="alignleft size-large is-resized"><a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B096KZ2XTY" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="2807" data-permalink="http://ellenmint.blog/amazon-logo-black-square-300x300-1/" data-orig-file="https://ellenmint.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/amazon-logo-black-square-300x300-1.png" data-orig-size="300,300" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{

}" data-image-title="capture" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://thoughtsdepart.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/capture.png?w=291" data-large-file="https://thoughtsdepart.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/capture.png?w=608" src="https://thoughtsdepart.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/capture.png?w=608" alt="" class="wp-image-743" srcset="https://thoughtsdepart.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/capture.png 608w, https://thoughtsdepart.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/capture.png?w=146 146w, https://thoughtsdepart.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/capture.png?w=291 291w" sizes="(max-width: 608px) 100vw, 608px" /></figure></div>


<p>This morning I was sitting in my bed. It is situated in a position that lets me see out to the balcony while a well-placed mirror allows me to see the birds who grace me with their songs and their joyful little natures. It is a delightful view and a wonderful distraction to the ramblings of my currently rather tired mind. Activity is an occupation I shall not be indulging in for some weeks to come and although I have never craved 100-mile hikes, I would be happy right now if I could just make it to the laundry room without feeling the three flights of stairs getting there and back possesses the same attributes as climbing Kanchenjunga.<br>Before my readers puzzle over my cryptic writing, I shall be open enough to admit I have recently undergone surgery to remove an organ which chose to misbehave and was causing me enough misery for me to agree with the medical profession that removal was the best course of action. As hysterectomies are quite common and a thoroughly run of the mill procedure everyone is familiar with, I shall not bore you any further. What the literature and all the learned pundits neglect to mention is what it actually means to rest for 6 weeks. Easier said than done, my friends. </p>



<p>Of course, a chair does not a balcony make. Though I do admit, these are quite comfortable particularly as they require no effort to turn into a lounge chair.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img data-attachment-id="671" data-permalink="https://thoughtsdepart.wordpress.com/2022/05/15/green-thumbs-and-well-thumbed-books/img_20220515_113909/" data-orig-file="https://thoughtsdepart.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/img_20220515_113909.jpg" data-orig-size="3072,4096" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{

}" data-image-title="img_20220515_113909" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://thoughtsdepart.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/img_20220515_113909.jpg?w=225" data-large-file="https://thoughtsdepart.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/img_20220515_113909.jpg?w=768" src="https://thoughtsdepart.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/img_20220515_113909.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-671" /></figure>



<p>What makes a balcony is the plants.</p>



