<p>Unfortunately, Book the cook options are currently limited out of NYC because of COVID measures and limitations. But nonetheless I tried it and booked <strong>Stir Fry chicken in Chinese wine sauce</strong> with veggies and jasmine rice. Quite fragrant and tasty.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="12752" data-permalink="http://gastronomictraveler.blog/2022/05/15/review-worlds-longest-flight-on-singapore-airlines-sq23-jfk-sin-in-business-class/pxl_20220505_042318760/" data-orig-file="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_042318760.jpeg" data-orig-size="368,654" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{

}" data-image-title="PXL_20220505_042318760" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_042318760.jpeg?w=169" data-large-file="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_042318760.jpeg?w=368" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-12752" src="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_042318760.jpeg" alt="PXL_20220505_042318760" width="368" height="654" srcset="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_042318760.jpeg 368w, https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_042318760.jpeg?w=84&h=150 84w, https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_042318760.jpeg?w=169&h=300 169w" sizes="(max-width: 368px) 100vw, 368px" /></p>
<p>The crew were very proactive in refilling my water. Mixed offerings of refilling the wine occasionally got offered and occasionally had to ask, but most of the time they offered.</p>
<p>Meal wrapped up with Ben and Jerry’s Rocky Road ice cream for dessert. The post-departure service took around 1.5-2 hours, quite efficient.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="12753" data-permalink="http://gastronomictraveler.blog/2022/05/15/review-worlds-longest-flight-on-singapore-airlines-sq23-jfk-sin-in-business-class/pxl_20220505_043857630/" data-orig-file="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_043857630.jpeg" data-orig-size="368,654" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{

}" data-image-title="PXL_20220505_043857630" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_043857630.jpeg?w=169" data-large-file="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_043857630.jpeg?w=368" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-12753" src="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_043857630.jpeg" alt="PXL_20220505_043857630" width="368" height="654" srcset="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_043857630.jpeg 368w, https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_043857630.jpeg?w=84&h=150 84w, https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_043857630.jpeg?w=169&h=300 169w" sizes="(max-width: 368px) 100vw, 368px" /></p>
<p>When asked if I needed anything else such as coffee, tea, digestif, I said I was ok but asked for the amenity kit and as mentioned was told not available but was promptly brought slippers, eye mask and socks. I then changed into my own pajamas (funnily enough I brought QR Q Suites PJs), as SQ does not provide pajamas in business class.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="12754" data-permalink="http://gastronomictraveler.blog/2022/05/15/review-worlds-longest-flight-on-singapore-airlines-sq23-jfk-sin-in-business-class/pxl_20220505_051501230/" data-orig-file="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_051501230.jpeg" data-orig-size="368,654" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{

}" data-image-title="PXL_20220505_051501230" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_051501230.jpeg?w=169" data-large-file="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_051501230.jpeg?w=368" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-12754" src="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_051501230.jpeg" alt="PXL_20220505_051501230" width="368" height="654" srcset="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_051501230.jpeg 368w, https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_051501230.jpeg?w=84&h=150 84w, https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_051501230.jpeg?w=169&h=300 169w" sizes="(max-width: 368px) 100vw, 368px" /></p>
<p>When I returned to my seat, my glass and empty water bottle had been cleared and replaced with a new water bottle. Though this ended up being the only time an empty water bottle I had was replaced during the flight, regardless still appreciate that attention to detail and proactive service. I did notice a downside to the wide seats, is it can be harder for the flight attendants to reach over you to clear away items on your armrest/storage area.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="12758" data-permalink="http://gastronomictraveler.blog/2022/05/15/review-worlds-longest-flight-on-singapore-airlines-sq23-jfk-sin-in-business-class/pxl_20220505_100658535/" data-orig-file="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_100658535.jpeg" data-orig-size="368,654" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{

}" data-image-title="PXL_20220505_100658535" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_100658535.jpeg?w=169" data-large-file="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_100658535.jpeg?w=368" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-12758" src="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_100658535.jpeg" alt="PXL_20220505_100658535" width="368" height="654" srcset="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_100658535.jpeg 368w, https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_100658535.jpeg?w=84&h=150 84w, https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_100658535.jpeg?w=169&h=300 169w" sizes="(max-width: 368px) 100vw, 368px" /></p>
<p>The flight attendants do offer to turn your seat into a bed. I decided to try for myself, and found it to be fairly intuitive and easy. You lift a latch in the back of the seat, fold it over, extend the mattress pad, and voila, a bed! There are two extra pillows provided as well. Total 3 pillows, a blanket and mattress pad, yes its a bit on the firmer side, but I dont mind, still found it to be a comfortable bed. Even more so in the bulkhead with all that extra room to stretch and move your feet and ability to sleep straight, though knowing how I often sleep, I’d have been ok with my feet in the cozy footwell, sleeping on my side/ at an angle.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="12756" data-permalink="http://gastronomictraveler.blog/2022/05/15/review-worlds-longest-flight-on-singapore-airlines-sq23-jfk-sin-in-business-class/pxl_20220505_053110227/" data-orig-file="https://garythegastronomictraveler.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pxl_20220505_053110227.jpeg" data-orig-size="368,654" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{

