<p>We had enough time on our final morning in Den Haag to hop on our bicycles once again and ride to the beach. Photos of sand dunes, kilometres of fine sandy beaches, and the Schevenigan pier in the distance will need to wait for our return.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><a href="https://lifephasenext.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/20220508_113843.jpg"><img data-attachment-id="15299" data-permalink="http://lifephasenext.com/20220508_113843/" data-orig-file="https://lifephasenext.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/20220508_113843.jpg" data-orig-size="1200,900" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{

}" data-image-title="image" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://rebekahthebacon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/image.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://rebekahthebacon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/image.png?w=640" src="https://rebekahthebacon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/image.png?w=640" alt="" class="wp-image-1034" srcset="https://rebekahthebacon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/image.png 640w, https://rebekahthebacon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/image.png?w=150 150w, https://rebekahthebacon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/image.png?w=300 300w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /><figcaption><a href="https://www.tumblr.com/tagged/tara+lynne+o'neill">Image Source</a></figcaption></figure></div>


<p class="has-small-font-size">As much as the girls (and James) are the centre of the show, that doesn’t take away from the character development and depth given to other periphery characters. By watching the show we learn so much about the mothers, coming to love them in their own right as much as Uncle Colm, Father Peter, Sister Micheal, and Tina O’Connell. This paints a picture of the wide variety of people in Derry, whilst recognising in life it’s always the same people cropping up. Lisa McGee pays tribute to this somewhat by taking us into the school years of the mothers, showing how the people around us influence and shape our histories.</p>



<p class="has-small-font-size">The final reason why I love Derry girls that I will mention is because of all the men. Fairly regularly within the series, the scene is built up to present a man as a heartthrob, someone desirable and utterly irresistible. In every single one of these cases, the man has been the most generic representation of a man possible. There are no rippling abs, sharp cheekbones or anything particularly out of the ordinary. The men look like the sort of men you are likely to have come in to fix the boiler or to meet in a service station. It’s the kickback at media representations that people have to look a certain way to be attractive because, as in real life, most people don’t look like the posters. In fact, we don’t want people to look like the posters – we want people who are real. Attractiveness is entirely defined by the viewer and we are all viewers. Sometimes all that requires is someone doing house maintenance just after you’ve read a steamy chapter about Heathcliff. </p>


