<figure class="aligncenter size-large"><img data-attachment-id="1036" data-permalink="https://rebekahthebacon.wordpress.com/2022/05/15/teenagers-troubles-and-irish-accents/image-1-5/" data-orig-file="https://rebekahthebacon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/image-1.png" data-orig-size="540,335" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{

}" data-image-title="image-1" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://rebekahthebacon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/image-1.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://rebekahthebacon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/image-1.png?w=540" src="https://rebekahthebacon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/image-1.png?w=540" alt="" class="wp-image-1036" srcset="https://rebekahthebacon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/image-1.png 540w, https://rebekahthebacon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/image-1.png?w=150 150w, https://rebekahthebacon.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/image-1.png?w=300 300w" sizes="(max-width: 540px) 100vw, 540px" /><figcaption><a href="https://www.tumgir.com/tag/father%20peter">Image Source</a></figcaption></figure></div>


<p class="has-small-font-size">I don’t necessarily think Derry Girls is underrated, that’s not why I’m writing this. Instead, I know it is an incredible show and many people enjoy it. But I think it manages to do something few other TV shows are doing. It shows the comedy of real life as it is, with all of the serious and important parts of life, with people who look like those we see every day and act like them too. The show represents teenagers and their resilience, taking us alongside them as they live through historic moments in Ireland’s reconciliation. If you haven’t watched it, you need to change that and if you have, you need to watch it again.</p>



