<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><a href="https://peripateticbone.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/salt-creek-death-valley.jpeg"><img data-attachment-id="32922" data-permalink="http://wandering-through-time-and-place.com/2022/05/15/what-color-would-a-death-valley-artist-paint-a-pupfish-in-love/salt-creek-death-valley/" data-orig-file="https://peripateticbone.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/salt-creek-death-valley.jpeg" data-orig-size="5472,3648" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{

}" data-image-title="Pupfish breeding NP" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://peripateticbone.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pupfish-breeding-np.jpeg?w=300" data-large-file="https://peripateticbone.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pupfish-breeding-np.jpeg?w=1024" src="https://peripateticbone.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pupfish-breeding-np.jpeg?w=1024" alt="" class="wp-image-32921" srcset="https://peripateticbone.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pupfish-breeding-np.jpeg?w=1024 1024w, https://peripateticbone.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pupfish-breeding-np.jpeg?w=2048 2048w, https://peripateticbone.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pupfish-breeding-np.jpeg?w=150 150w, https://peripateticbone.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pupfish-breeding-np.jpeg?w=300 300w, https://peripateticbone.files.wordpress.com/2022/05/pupfish-breeding-np.jpeg?w=768 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a><figcaption>An information panel gave an artist’s rendition of a happy couple. “But where’s the blue?” went dashing through my head. Remember the old “Where’s the beef?” commercials. Okay, I admit that there is some blue, and it is on the male. The panel described the mating process. And it isn’t even R-rated. A female arrives in the males territory, swims over to him, and snuggles up to his side. They start shivering in anticipation, and zoom, she’s pregnant. Just like that. I’d say something about being premature but apparently, that’s how it’s done.  “Was it good for you, honey?”</figcaption></figure>



<p>When you watch pupfish for a while they appear to be playful, dashing around, chasing each other, and plowing up the dirt with their noses. That’s where they get the name pupfish.  We wished this year’s crop good luck and I took a final photo of the creek as we headed off for out next adventure: exploring Mosaic Canyon, which will be our next post.</p>



